\section{Background}
\subsection{Reinforcement learning} \label{sec:Reinforcement learning}
This section aims to explain the core concepts of reinforcement learning and related theories.
\\\\
The fundamentals of reinforcement learning involve an \textit{agent} that interacts with an \textit{environment} by making \textit{observations}, taking \textit{actions}, and receiving \textit{rewards}. This process can be seen in Figure \ref{fig:2.1Reinforcement learning}:

\begin{figure} [h!]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.5\linewidth]{Template/Figures/2.1Reinforcement.png}
    \caption{The interaction between agent and environment, \cite{sutton2018reinforcement}, p.48}
    \label{fig:2.1Reinforcement learning}
\end{figure}
\noindent where $S_t$ is the state, $R_t$ is the reward and $A_t$ is the action at time t. The objective of the agent is to learn a behavior that maximizes the cumulative reward over time, denoted as $G_t$. The formula for maximizing the expected discounted return can be seen below (\cite{sutton2018reinforcement}, p.55, eq 3.8):

\begin{equation}
    G_t = R_{t+1} + \gamma R_{t+2} + \gamma^2 R_{t+3} + ... + \gamma^{T-1} R_{T} 
\end{equation}
where T is the terminal date and $\gamma\in(0,1]$ is a discount factor. 
\\\\
In addition to the agent and environment, other important elements of reinforcement learning are a policy, a reward signal, and a value function. A policy $\pi$ defines how the agent behaves at a given state, in practice mapping states to actions, which is written as $A_t = \pi(S_t)$ at time $t$. When the reinforcement algorithm advances the policy updates. The reward signal specifies the goal of the learning process by providing immediate feedback on the agent’s actions. The value function, in contrast, evaluates the long-term desirability of states or actions by estimating expected future rewards (\cite{sutton2018reinforcement}, page 6).

\subsection{Financial Background}
This section provides an overview of key concepts in derivatives and hedging, related to this master thesis.   

\subsubsection{Options}
Options are financial derivatives that grant the right, but not the obligation, to either buy or sell an asset at a predetermined price (the strike price) on or before a specified date. Options may therefore be either call options or put options, and they are further classified according to the flexibility of their exercise date. One of the simplest variants is the European option, which can only be exercised at maturity. A call option generates profit if the price of the underlying asset rises above the strike price, while a put option becomes profitable if the price falls below the strike price (\cite{investments}, p.51-52). It is also possible to write an option, meaning that an investor sells an option contract they do not own, thereby assuming the obligation to fulfill the contract terms should the buyer choose to exercise the option. In exchange for bearing this risk, the option writer receives a premium. These features give rise to four basic options positions: long call, short call, long put, and short put. 

\subsubsection{Black-Scholes}
Black-Scholes provides a theoretical framework for option pricing. Under this model, the value of an option is assumed to be affected by the following factors: 
(i) the price of the underlying asset, 
(ii) the strike price, 
(iii) the volatility of the underlying asset, 
(iv) the risk-free interest rate, and 
(v) the time to maturity. The value of a European call option is given by the following formula (\cite{investments}, p.725, eq.21.1)
\begin{equation}
C_0 = S_0 N(d_1) - X e^{-rT} N(d_2)
\label{eq:bs_call}
\end{equation}

where
\begin{equation*}
d_1 = \frac{\ln(S_0 / X) + \left(r + \frac{\sigma^2}{2}\right)T}{\sigma \sqrt{T}},
\qquad
d_2 = d_1 - \sigma \sqrt{T}.
\end{equation*}

\begin{align*}
C_0 & = \text{current call option value}, \\
S_0 & = \text{current stock price}, \\
N(d) & = \text{cumulative distribution function of the standard normal distribution}, \\
X & = \text{exercise (strike) price}, \\
r & = \text{risk-free interest rate (continuously compounded)}, \\
T & = \text{time to expiration (in years)}, \\
\sigma & = \text{standard deviation of the stock's continuously compounded return}.
\end{align*}

\subsubsection{Hedging}
Hedging is a strategy aimed at limiting risk in investments and is commonly used when trading derivatives, such as options. To hedge risk connected to derivatives, traders can monitor various sensitivities of a derivative’s value, commonly referred to as the Greek letters. These sensitivities capture how the value of a position responds to changes in key market variables, such as the underlying asset price (delta), volatility (vega), the passage of time (theta), and interest rates (rho). One of the most important Greek letters is delta, which represents how sensitive the derivative is to a change in the underlying asset. In practice, traders often seek to maintain delta-neutral positions, thereby reducing exposure to small price movements in the underlying asset. Since the delta changes over time, a trader’s hedge must be adjusted through periodic rebalancing. In a frictionless market, where transaction costs and other market imperfections are absent, the theoretically optimal strategy involves continuous rebalancing. However, real markets are characterized by transaction costs and various trading frictions (\cite{cao2020deephedging}, p.1-2).


