\subsubsection{Markov Decision Process}
In reinforcement learning, the probability of the next state and the reward only depends on the current state and action. This characteristic is known as the Markov property and is defined as (\cite{sutton2018reinforcement} on page 48, equation 3.2): 
 \begin{equation}
     p(s',r | s,a) = Pr(S_{t} = s', R_{t} = r | S_{t - 1} = s, A_{t-1} = a)
     \label{eq:Markov Property}
 \end{equation}
When the sets of states S, actions A, and rewards R are finite, together with this probability function, they define a finite Markov decision process (MDP). MDP is a mathematical framework for modeling sequential decision-making in environments with uncertain outcomes. In reinforcement learning, an action influences not only the immediate reward but also future outcomes, since the chosen action affects the state in which the agent will subsequently find itself. Consequently, decision-making in MDPs involves a trade-off between immediate and delayed rewards. The journey that the agent takes through the MDP is known as its trajectory. To guide the selection of a policy that maximizes cumulative reward, state value functions, $v_\pi(s)$, or action value functions, $q_\pi(s,a)$, are used. State value function, estimates the expected return from a given state, and the action value function, estimates the expected return from taking a specific action in a given state (\cite{sutton2018reinforcement}, page 71 eq 3.12.). \todo{Add about transition probabilities}


\subsubsection{Value Functions}

The framework for a Markov decision process is defined by the state-value function. $v_\pi(s)$ as the expected value when an agent stands in state $s$ and following the policy $\pi$:
 \begin{equation}
     v_\pi(s) = \mathbb{E}[G_t | S_t = s ] = \mathbb{E}[\sum_{k=0}^\infty \gamma ^k R_{t+k+1 } | S_t = s] \label{eq:value function 3.10}
 \end{equation}
where $ \mathbb{E}_\pi[.]$ denotes the expected value of a random variable given that the agent follows policy $\pi$ and $t$ at any time step, and $\gamma \in [0,1]$ is the discount factor which weights immediate rewards against future rewards. 
\\
\\
The action-value function function, $q_\pi(s,a)$ is the expected value if the agents takes an action, $a$, from state, $s$, and following the policy $\pi$: 


\begin{equation}
    q_\pi(s,a) = \mathbb{E}[G_t | S_t = s, A_t = a] = \mathbb{E}[\sum_{k=0}^\infty \gamma ^k R_{t+k+1 } | S_t = s, A_t = a] 
    \label{eq: action-value function 3.11}
\end{equation}



\subsubsection{Bellman equation}\label{sec:Bellman equation}

The Bellman equation provides the connecting web of our subspace, i.e., the subspace that the agent needs to transverse(?). The Bellman equation allows us to convert the information of the environment into an improvement of the agent's behavior. It is a universal concept in the world of sequential decision-making. 
\\
\\
The Bellman equation connects all the state values, it allows us to convert information of the environment into improvements of the agents behavior. The value function can be expressed recursive, and the bellman equation breaks down the state in the imitiate reward plus the discontinued value of the later rewards. For the state value funciton, $v_\pi(s)$ it¨s defined as:

\begin{equation}
    v_\pi(s) = \mathbb{E}[G_t | S_t = s] = \sum_a \pi(a|s) \sum _{s´,a}p(s',r|s,a) [r+\gamma v_\pi(s')]\label{eq: Bellman-equation value function 3.12}
\end{equation} 
where its implicit that the action, a, are taken from the set $ A(s)$. and the next state $s'$ are taken from the set $S$, and the rewards, $r$, are taken from the set $R$.(\cite{sutton2018reinforcement}, page 70 eq 3.12).
The equations is a sum of all three valiables, are for each tripple, we compute its probability, $\pi(a|s)p(s',r|s,a)$
\\

\subsubsection{Optimal value function}
Solving reinforcement learning tasks means finding a policy that achives a lot of rewards, for a finite MDP. There exists an optimal policy, (could be more than one), its denoted $\pi_*$. The optimal state valur function is deoted $ v_*$ and defined as
The optimal 0
\begin{equation}
    v_*(s) = max_\pi v_\pi(s),
\end{equation}
for all $ s\in S$.
The optimal policy for the action-value function is defined as 
\begin{equation}
        q_*(s,a) = max_\pi q_\pi(s,a),
\end{equation}
for all $ s\in S$ and $a\in A$. $q_*$ can be written in terms of $v_*$:
 
\begin{equation}
    q_*(s,a) = \mathbb{E}[R_{t+1} + \gamma v_*(S_{t+a} | S_t = s, A_t = a] = \sum_a \pi(a|s) \sum _{s´,a}p(s',r|s,a) [r+\gamma v_\pi(s')]\label{eq: Bellman-equation action_value function 3.15}
\end{equation}

\subsubsection{Dynamic Programming}  
Dynamic programming refer to algorithms that can find optimal policies, given a perfect model of the environment.  It refers to the algorithms used to find optimal policies which have complete knowledge of the environment as a Markov decision process. In other words, Dynamic Programming has access to $p(s', r | s, a)$ (policy). (An unrealistic assumption in the real world)

\subsubsection{Policy evaluation}
Compute the state value function, $v_\pi(s)$ or action value function, $q_\pi(s,a)$ for a given policy, $\pi$, for all states or state action pairs, under some MDP (Markov decision process). 
Starting by randomly initializing the state values, and then calculating \begin{equation}
    V(s) \xleftarrow[]{} \sum_{a\in A(s)}\pi(a | s) \sum_{s'\in S,  r \in R} p(s', r | s, a)´[r + \gamma V(s')].
\end{equation}
(V(s) is capital since we estimate the true values)
One repeat over all states is called a sweep, and this is done until the state values converge. (We use the Bellman equation, \ref{eq: Bellman-equation value function 3.12}, and it always converges for an mdp). 
