\subsubsection{Generalized Policy Iteration}
\epigraph{\enquote{GPI refers to the general idea of letting policy evaluation and policy imporovement process interact, independent of the granularity and other detalis of the two processes. Almost all reinforcement learning methods are well described as GPI}}{---\textit{Sutton, Barto\\ Reinforcement learning book}}
GPI is a class of algorithms: \\
\textbf{Policy improvement:} To find $\pi_*$ and $v_*$, \begin{equation}
    \pi_0 \xrightarrow{\mathbb{E}} v_{\pi_0} \xrightarrow{I} \pi_1 \xrightarrow{\mathbb{E}} v_{\pi_1} \xrightarrow{I} \pi_2
 \xrightarrow{\mathbb{E}}\dots \xrightarrow{I}.
 \end{equation}
This is done until the value function stops changing. \\
\textbf{Value iteration}: Another GPI algorithm.\\
\\

\subsubsection{Monte Carlo Methods}
In dynamic programming, it is assumed that there is perfect knowledge of the environment. When such a model is unavailable or impractical to obtain, Monte Carlo methods provide an alternative approach based solely on sampled experience. 
\\\\
Monte Carlo methods are model-free and rely on observed episodes consisting of states, actions, and rewards. Instead of using a known model, these methods estimate value functions by computing sample averages of returns, thereby approximating expected future rewards (\cite{sutton2018reinforcement}, p.91). The update rule when using Monte Carlo methods can be seen bellow: 

\begin{equation}
    Q(S_{t}, A_{t}) \xleftarrow{} Q(S_{t}, A_{t}) + \alpha(G_{t} - Q(S_{t}, A_{t}))
    \label{eq: Monte Carlo for Q function}
\end{equation}
where $\alpha \in (0,1]$ is a constant parameter. In Monte Carlo methods the update is performed after an episode is completed.


\subsubsection{On- and Off-Policy methods}
In reinforcement learning, the difference between on-policy and off-policy methods lies in the relationship between the policy used to generate the data  and the policy being evaluated/improved. In on-policy learning, the agent evaluates and improves the same policy that it uses to interact with the environment. Consequently, learning is based directly on the actions taken by the current policy. In contrast, off-policy learning separates these roles by allowing the agent to learn about one policy, referred to as the target policy, while following a different policy, known as the behavior policy, to generate data. This separation makes the methods more powerful and general, but the downside is that they are often of greater variance and are slower to converge (\cite{sutton2018reinforcement}, p.103).

