\subsubsection{Function Approximation}
In many reinforcement learning problems, the state or action spaces are too large to allow for an exact tabular representation of value functions. In such cases, function approximation is used to generalize value estimates across states or state–action pairs. Instead of storing separate estimates for each state, a parameterized function is employed to represent the value function. Formally, the value function is approximated as $\hat{v}=(s,w)$ or $\hat{q}=(s,a,w)$, where w denotes a vector of adjustable parameters. These parameters are updated using data obtained through interaction with the environment, enabling the agent to improve its estimates even for previously unvisited states. Function approximation can be implemented using for example neural networks (\cite{sutton2018reinforcement}, p.197). 

\subsubsection{Policy Gradient Methods}
"Directly using arg max() to determine a policy is suitable when the action space is discrete and not too large. However, when the action space is continuous, this method becomes impractical as it involves a global maximization at every step. An alternative approach, known as policy gradients, learns the optimal policy directly. The basic idea is to represent the policy by a parametric function $\pi(St; \theta)$, where $\theta$ is the parameter vector. Learning is then done through exploring the environment and adjusting the policy parameters in the direction of greater action values. " (\cite{cao2020deephedging}, page 6)


\subsection{Actor Critic}
Actor-critic combines both Policy-based methods(Learning straight from a policy) and Value-based methods(Leaning a value function). \\
\\
Actor-critic is a Temporal difference version of policy gradients. It is two networks, the actor and the critic, where the actor takes the decisions and the critic validates them.
The actor represents the policy and decides what action to take, i.e $\pi_\theta(a|s)$, and is updated to make better decisions. The critic on the other hand is validating how well the actor performed by either using the value function, $V^\pi(s)$ or the action-value function $Q^\pi(s,a)$ and it is calculating the TD-error. 


\begin{equation}
    \delta_t = R_{t+1} + \gamma V(s') -V(s)
\end{equation}
(p.121, eq 6.5, \cite{sutton2018reinforcement}). The TD error is updating the actor in the direction that will maximize the reward, weighted by $\delta$.

 
